
# Campus Recruitment Prediction With Machine Learning for MBA Students

This project was undertaken as an individual assignment during the 5th semester and involved predicting campus recruitment outcomes using machine learning techniques.


## Project Overview


The main objectives of the project were:

- Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and Data Visualization: The project began with an in-depth exploration of the dataset to understand the characteristics and relationships of the variables. Various data visualization techniques were employed to gain insights into the data.
- Data Preprocessing: Preprocessing steps included handling categorical features using LabelEncoder, scaling numerical features to ensure uniformity in their influence, and addressing the imbalance in the dataset using the Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE).
- Modeling: The project utilized a Support Vector Machine (SVM) model for its classification capabilities, which are well-suited for binary outcomes like recruitment prediction.
- Grid Search and ROC Curve: Hyperparameter tuning was performed using Grid Search to find the optimal parameters for the SVM model. The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve was used to evaluate the performance of the model and visualize the trade-off between true positive rate and false positive rate.
